Analysis Summary

In order to complete the given assignment, the following three topics,which are fairly unrelated were chosen -


1) Cricket
2) BJP
3) Analytics

  1. Based upon this exercise, it is fairly evident that the Topic Model is able to segregate each subject from other subjects/topics and align all the tokens to corresponding subjects/topics. The success rate on this exercise is believed to be more than 90%. The word cloud specific to each subject/token is a testimony to the success rate of the Topic Model used.

    We identified these incorrect alignments with subjects/topics in 100 tokens word clouds. The incorrectly aligned tokens are -
    1. “Champions_Trophy” under Analytics topic
    2. “Cricket_au”, “Google_Analytics” and “play_play” under BJP topic.

  2. No tokens with high LIFT in more than one topic was identified and rightly so. Almost in all the cases that were reviewed, the LIFT tokens and the document topic proportions (ETA scores) are clearly distinguishable and able to identify subjects/topics. We believe the success to this correct identification has a dependency on how strongly unrelated subjects/topics are. We also increased the value of K from 3 to 4 to further split the entire corpus into 4 different topics and found out that the probability of each term with respect to each topic got changed and became closer to other values for the same token/term.
  3. The learning from this exercise are -

  1. More unrelated topics are, the better probability of correct alignment of tokens. However, in the real world business problems, the corpus will be already there and this Topic Model can help the user to dissect the corpus with respect to n-number of different topics where n is defined by the user himself/herself.

  2. Irrespective of whether the segregation are close to accurate, we still believe that data analyst intervention is highly recommended to understand the segregation and draw out the right business correlations.

Function to clean the corpus

  1. Remove HTML tags.
  2. Keep only ASCII characters
  3. Keep only alpha numeric
  4. Remove numbers
  5. Remove white space
text.clean = function(x)                    # text data
{ require("tm")
  x  =  gsub("<.*?>", " ", x)               # regex for removing HTML tags
  x  =  iconv(x, "latin1", "ASCII", sub="") # Keep only ASCII characters
  x  =  gsub("[^[:alnum:]]", " ", x)        # keep only alpha numeric 
  x  =  tolower(x)                          # convert to lower case characters
  x  =  removeNumbers(x)                    # removing numbers
  x  =  stripWhitespace(x)                  # removing white space
  x  =  gsub("^\\s+|\\s+$", "", x)          # remove leading and trailing white space
  return(x)
}

Funcion - to create COG (Co-occurrence Graph)

distill.cog = function(mat1, # input TCM ADJ MAT
                       title, # title for the graph
                       s,    # no. of central nodes
                       k1){  # max no. of connections  
  
  a = colSums(mat1) # collect colsums into a vector obj a
  b = order(-a)     # nice syntax for ordering vector in decr order  
  
  mat2 = mat1[b,b]  #
  
  diag(mat2) =  0
  
  ## +++ go row by row and find top k adjacencies +++ ##
  
  wc = NULL
  
  for (i1 in 1:s){ 
    thresh1 = mat2[i1,][order(-mat2[i1, ])[k1]]
    mat2[i1, mat2[i1,] < thresh1] = 0   # wow. didn't need 2 use () in the subset here.
    mat2[i1, mat2[i1,] > 0 ] = 1
    word = names(mat2[i1, mat2[i1,] > 0])
    mat2[(i1+1):nrow(mat2), match(word,colnames(mat2))] = 0
    wc = c(wc,word)
  } # i1 loop ends
  
  
  mat3 = mat2[match(wc, colnames(mat2)), match(wc, colnames(mat2))]
  ord = colnames(mat2)[which(!is.na(match(colnames(mat2), colnames(mat3))))]  # removed any NAs from the list
  mat4 = mat3[match(ord, colnames(mat3)), match(ord, colnames(mat3))]
  graph <- graph.adjacency(mat4, mode = "undirected", weighted=T)    # Create Network object
  graph = simplify(graph) 
  V(graph)$color[1:s] = "green"
  V(graph)$color[(s+1):length(V(graph))] = "pink"
  
  graph = delete.vertices(graph, V(graph)[ degree(graph) == 0 ])
  
  plot(graph, 
       layout = layout.kamada.kawai, 
      main = title)

  } # func ends

Compute LIFT for all terms across all topics

tst = round(ncol(dtm)/100)
a = rep(tst,99)
b = cumsum(a);rm(a)
b = c(0,b,ncol(dtm))

ss.col = c(NULL)
for (i in 1:(length(b)-1)) {
  tempdtm = dtm[,(b[i]+1):(b[i+1])]
  s = colSums(as.matrix(tempdtm))
  ss.col = c(ss.col,s)
  #print(i)
}

theta = simfit$theta
lift = theta*0;       # lift will have same dimn as the theta matrix

sum1 = sum(dtm)
pterms = ss.col/sum1     # each column's marginal occurrence probability

for (i in 1:nrow(theta)){  
  for (j in 1:ncol(theta)){
    ptermtopic = 0; pterm = 0;
    ptermtopic = theta[i, j]
    pterm = pterms[i]
    lift[i, j] = ptermtopic/pterm     # divide each cell by the column's marg. occurr. proby.
  }
}

Calculate ETA - each document’s score on each topic

t = Sys.time()

if(nrow(dtm) < 100) {k1 = 10} else {k1= 100}   # to avoid machine choking up in v small datasets

tst = ceiling(nrow(dtm)/k1)  # now using 1% of the rows at a time
a = rep(tst, (k1 - 1))
b = cumsum(a);rm(a)    # cumsum() is cumulative sum.
b = c(0, b, nrow(dtm))  # broke the supermassive dtm into chunks of 1% ncol each
  a0 = which(b > nrow(dtm));    # sometimes, rounding errors cause out of bound errors
  if (length(a0) > 0) {b = b[-a0]}

eta.new = NULL
for (i1 in 1:K){
  
  a2 = c(NULL)
  for (i in 1:(length(b)-1)) {
    tempdtm = dtm[(b[i]+1):(b[i+1]),]
    a = matrix(rep(lift[, i1], nrow(tempdtm)), nrow(tempdtm), ncol(tempdtm), byrow = TRUE)
    a1 = rowSums(as.matrix(tempdtm * a))
    a2 = c(a2, a1); rm(a, a1, tempdtm)
      } # i ends
  
  eta.new = cbind(eta.new, a2); rm(a2)
  
  } # i1 ends

Sys.time() - t  # will take longer than lift building coz ncol is v v high now
## Time difference of 0.058568 secs
rownames(eta.new) = rownames(simfit$omega)
colnames(eta.new) = colnames(simfit$theta)

df.top.terms = data.frame(NULL)    # can't fit ALL terms in plot, so choose top ones with max loading

for (i in 1:K){       # For each topic 
  a0 = which(censored.lift[,i] > 1) # terms with lift greator than 1 for topic i
  freq = theta[a0, i] # Theta for terms greator than 1
  freq = sort(freq, decreasing = T) # Terms with higher probilities for topic i
  
  # Auto Correction -  Sometime terms in topic with lift above 1 are less than 100. So auto correction
  n = ifelse(length(freq) >= 100, 100, length(freq))
  top_word = as.matrix(freq[1:n])
  
  top.terms = row.names(top_word)
  df.top.terms.t = data.frame(topic = i, top.terms =top.terms, stringsAsFactors = F )
  df.top.terms = rbind(df.top.terms, df.top.terms.t  )
  
} # i loop ends

### which rows load most on which topics? ###

show.top.loading.rows = function(eta.obj, number.of.units){
  
  K = ncol(eta.obj)    # no. of topic factors
  n = number.of.units
  top.loaders = NULL
  for (i in 1:K){
    a0 = order(eta.obj[,i], decreasing = TRUE)
    a1 = rownames(eta.obj[a0[1:n],])
    top.loaders = cbind(a1, top.loaders)
  } # i loop ends

  a2 = matrix()
  return(top.loaders)
  
} # func ends
